vectorData.altText: 14. Fill in the blank: Identify B.
That's right!  ’B’ is the subclavian artery. TIP: the subclavian artery, as well as the roots of the brachial plexus, emerge from the neck posterior to the anterior scalene muscle.

of the omohyoid, and by dividing it if necessary, LOOK for the upper roots of the brachial plexus passing between the anterior and middle scalene muscles. The subclavian artery leaves the thorax by passing between the anterior and middle scalene in front of the lower fibers of the brachial plexus. The subclavian vein passes through the lower part of the posterior triangle in front of the anterior scalene to enter the thorax.
